# YAML Frontmatter Reference

Every SKILL.md file begins with a YAML frontmatter block delimited by `---`. This block controls skill behavior, tool access, triggering, and integration with the skill system.

---

## Complete Frontmatter Template

```yaml
---
# ============================================================
# REQUIRED FIELDS
# ============================================================

name: {{SKILL_NAME}}
# Kebab-case identifier. Used as the slash command name.
# Examples: investigate, ship, qa, plan-ceo-review
# Convention: lowercase, hyphens for spaces, no underscores

version: {{VERSION}}
# Semantic versioning: MAJOR.MINOR.PATCH
# Bump MAJOR for breaking changes to skill behavior
# Bump MINOR for new phases or capabilities
# Bump PATCH for fixes and refinements
# Example: 1.0.0, 2.3.1

description: |
  {{LINE_1_SUMMARY}}
  {{LINE_2_TRIGGERS}}
  {{LINE_3_PROACTIVE}}
  {{LINE_4_DISAMBIGUATION}}
# Line 1: Imperative summary of what the skill does.
#   "Systematically debug issues with root cause investigation."
#
# Line 2: Trigger phrases. Start with "Use when asked to..."
#   "Use when asked to 'debug this', 'fix this bug', or 'investigate this error'."
#
# Line 3: Proactive triggers. Start with "Proactively suggest when..."
#   "Proactively suggest when the user reports errors or unexpected behavior."
#
# Line 4: Disambiguation. Start with "For..."
#   "For QA testing, use /qa instead."
#
# This field does double duty: it is both human-readable documentation
# AND the trigger text that the skill system uses to decide when to
# invoke this skill. Write it carefully.

# ============================================================
# PREAMBLE CONFIGURATION
# ============================================================

preamble-tier: {{1-4}}
# Controls how much scaffolding the skill gets:
#
# Tier 1 (Lightweight):
#   Core session tracking, upgrade check, telemetry, trimmed voice.
#   Use for: browse commands, single-task utilities, read-only tools.
#
# Tier 2 (Standard):
#   Tier 1 + full voice directive, AskUserQuestion format,
#   Completeness Principle with effort table.
#   Use for: debugging, analysis, retrospectives.
#
# Tier 3 (Full Context):
#   Tier 2 + repo mode (solo/collaborative), Search Before Building,
#   contributor mode.
#   Use for: brainstorming, planning, strategy, architecture review.
#
# Tier 4 (Workflow):
#   Tier 3 + test failure triage (in-branch vs pre-existing),
#   cross-skill orchestration, advanced stop/continue logic.
#   Use for: ship, QA, code review, deploy workflows.

# ============================================================
# TOOL ACCESS CONTROL
# ============================================================

allowed-tools:
  - Bash
  - Read
  - Edit
  - Write
  - Glob
  - Grep
  - AskUserQuestion
# Explicit whitelist. Skills can ONLY use tools listed here.
# This prevents scope creep: a brainstorming skill should not
# have Write access, a browse skill should not have Edit access.
#
# Common tool sets by skill type:
#
# Read-only analysis:    [Bash, Read, Glob, Grep, AskUserQuestion]
# Code modification:     [Bash, Read, Edit, Write, Glob, Grep, AskUserQuestion]
# Browse/QA:             [Bash, Read, Glob, Grep, AskUserQuestion, WebSearch]
# Planning (no code):    [Bash, Read, Glob, Grep, AskUserQuestion, Write]
#
# Note: AskUserQuestion should be in almost every skill.
# It is how skills communicate with the user.

# ============================================================
# OPTIONAL FIELDS
# ============================================================

benefits-from:
  - {{RELATED_SKILL_1}}
  - {{RELATED_SKILL_2}}
# Skills that enhance this one when available.
# Used by the skill system to suggest adjacent skills.
# Example: investigate benefits-from [browse] for visual debugging.

hooks:
  PreToolUse:
    - matcher: "{{TOOL_NAME}}"
      hooks:
        - type: command
          command: "{{SHELL_COMMAND}}"
# Pre-tool-use hooks run BEFORE the matched tool executes.
# Used for safety gates:
#   - Freeze: block edits outside a scoped directory
#   - Guard: warn before destructive commands
#   - Validation: check prerequisites before actions
#
# Example (freeze gate):
#   PreToolUse:
#     - matcher: "Edit"
#       hooks:
#         - type: command
#           command: "bash ~/.claude/skills/gstack/freeze/bin/check-freeze.sh"
---
```

---

## Field Quick Reference

| Field | Required | Type | Purpose |
|-------|----------|------|---------|
| `name` | Yes | string | Skill identifier and slash command |
| `version` | Yes | string | Semantic version for tracking changes |
| `description` | Yes | multi-line string | Human docs + machine trigger text |
| `preamble-tier` | Yes | integer (1-4) | Scaffolding complexity level |
| `allowed-tools` | Yes | string array | Tool whitelist (security boundary) |
| `benefits-from` | No | string array | Adjacent skill suggestions |
| `hooks` | No | object | Pre-tool safety gates |

---

## Common Mistakes

1. **Missing trigger phrases in description.** The description IS the trigger. If you do not include "Use when asked to..." the skill will not auto-invoke.

2. **Over-permissive tool list.** A planning skill with Write/Edit access will start modifying code. Restrict tools to what the skill actually needs.

3. **Wrong preamble tier.** A simple utility at Tier 4 wastes tokens on unnecessary scaffolding. A complex workflow at Tier 1 misses critical behavioral controls.

4. **No disambiguation line.** When two skills overlap (qa vs qa-only, investigate vs debug), the "For X, use /Y instead" line prevents the wrong skill from triggering.

5. **Forgetting AskUserQuestion in allowed-tools.** Without it, the skill cannot ask clarifying questions and will guess instead.
